==Overview== The Mendorinagayama Kofun is one of a cluster of tumuli located on a hillside approximately 900 meters from the {{ill|Sea of Japan|en|Sea of Japan|qid=Q27092|lt=Sea of Japan|1=Sea of Japan}} coast. The cluster consists of five tumuli, of which only the largest is a {{nihongo|{{ill|scallop-shaped kofun|lt=scallop-shaped tumulus|ja|帆立貝形古墳|1=scallop-shaped kofun|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/scallop-shaped kofun|13=User:Immanuelle/scallop-shaped kofun|comment=enwiki is a redirect}}|帆立貝形古墳|hotategai-gata kofun}} and is protected by the National Historic Site designation. The remaining tumuli in the site are all {{ill|Round Kofun|lt=circular-type|ja|円墳|1=Round Kofun|1=Round Kofun|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Round Kofun|13=User:Immanuelle/Round Kofun|comment=enwiki is a redirect}} (empun (円墳)) ''kofun''. <ref name="Shiseki">{{cite book |last1=Isomura |first1=Yukio |last2=Sakai |first2=Hideya |title=(国指定史跡事典) National Historic Site Encyclopedia |date=2012 |publisher=学生社 |isbn=4311750404}}{{in lang|ja}}</ref>
The largest of the group is Mendori No.5, which dates to the mid-5th century AD. The top was originally faced with ''[[fukiishi]]'' stones and had cylindrical ''{{ill|Haniwa|en|Haniwa|qid=Q849376|lt=Haniwa|1=Haniwa}}''. It has two horizontal [[:en:Burial chamber|Burial chamber]]s, but was robbed in ancient times. It was [[archaeological excavation|excavated]] from 2001 to 2006, and found to have two rectangular protrusions on its posterior domed portion. With the tumulus, fragments of a boat-shaped stone {{ill|Sarcophagus|en|Sarcophagus|qid=Q48634|lt=Sarcophagus|1=Sarcophagus}} made of local {{ill|Tuff|en|Tuff|qid=Q484924|lt=Tuff|1=Tuff}} and a decorated lid with a design of triangular and circular patterns, and fragmentary {{ill|Grave goods|en|Grave goods|qid=Q1399692|lt=Grave goods|1=Grave goods}}, including cylindrical and ''[[magatama]]'' beads have been found. Similar large-scale tombs of powerful local chieftains have been found in the Echizen area, but as a rule only in inland regions, such as the [[Rokuroseyama Kofun Cluster]] and the [[Matsuoka Kofun Cluster]]. This tomb is one of the largest of its type in the Hokuriku region, and is unusual in that the larger ''kofun'' found in {{ill|Echizen Province|en|Echizen Province|qid=Q1047144|lt=Echizen Province|1=Echizen Province}} were all located in the eastern end of the Fukui Plain along the basin of the [[:en:Kuzuryu River|Kuzuryu River]], and only this one is located so close to the coast. It is located about 50 minutes by car from {{ill|Fukui Station (Fukui)|en|Fukui Station (Fukui)|qid=Q867992|lt=Fukui Station|1=Fukui Station (Fukui)}} on the {{ill|West Japan Railway Company|en|West Japan Railway Company|qid=Q502125|lt=West Japan Railway Company|1=West Japan Railway Company}} {{ill|Hokuriku Main Line|en|Hokuriku Main Line|qid=Q1318747|lt=Hokuriku Main Line|1=Hokuriku Main Line}}. <ref name="Shiseki"/>
==The site== * Mendori No.1: This is a circular tumulus from the 5th century, with a diameter of 38 meters. * Mendori No.2: This is a circular tumulus from the 5th century, with a diameter of 20 meters. Its opening has been open since ancient times, and per local folklore was a hideout for pirates. * Mendori No.3: This is a circular tumulus from the 5th century, with a diameter of 35 meters. * Mendori No.4: This is a circular tumulus from the 5th century, with a diameter of 28 meters. * Mendori No.5: Also called the Mendorinagayama kofun: This is a scallop-shaped tumulus from the 5th century, with a length of 90.5 meters
